excite antagonist","Type II afferents inhibit antagonist and excite agonist","Type Ia afferents inhibit antagonist and excite agonist","Type Ib afferents inhibit antagonist and excite agonist"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Golgi tendon reflex involves \u003Cstrong\u003EType Ib afferent neurons\u003C/strong\u003E from Golgi tendon organs. When activated by increased muscle tension, these neurons trigger autogenic inhibition of the muscle containing the tendon organ while simultaneously exciting the antagonist muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ia afferents inhibit agonist and excite antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E - Type Ia afferents are found in muscle spindles and mediate the stretch reflex, not the Golgi tendon reflex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II afferents inhibit antagonist and excite agonist\u003C/strong\u003E - Type II afferents are secondary endings in muscle spindles that detect static muscle length\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ia afferents inhibit antagonist and excite agonist\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stretch reflex pathway, not the Golgi tendon reflex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ib afferents inhibit antagonist and excite agonist\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of the actual Golgi tendon reflex pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis protective reflex prevents excessive muscle tension that could potentially damage tendons or muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Golgi tendon organs contain Ib afferent neurons that detect muscle tension and force.","The Golgi tendon reflex causes autogenic inhibition of the muscle containing the tendon organ while exciting antagonist muscles.","This protective reflex prevents excessive muscle tension that could damage tendons or muscles."],"references":["Lyle MA, Nichols TR. Evaluating intermuscular Golgi tendon organ feedback with twitch contractions. J Physiol. 2019 Sep;597(17):4627-4642. doi: 10.1113/JP277363. Epub 2019 Jul 8. PMID: 31228207; PMCID: PMC6717046.","Chalmers G. Re-examination of the possible role of Golgi tendon organ and muscle spindle reflexes in proprioceptive neuromuscular facilitation muscle stretching. Sports Biomech. 2004 Jan;3(1):159-83. doi: 10.1080/14763140408522836. PMID: 15079994.","Oliver KM, Florez-Paz DM, Badea TC, Mentis GZ, Menon V, de Nooij JC. Molecular correlates of muscle spindle and Golgi tendon organ afferents. Nat Commun. 2021 Mar 1;12(1):1451. doi: 10.1038/s41467-021-21880-3. PMID: 33649316; PMCID: PMC7977083.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60914"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60914"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T19:31:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T19:32:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9217"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75404"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":